nly significant mock abuse is contained in `test_commands.py`, which appears to be intentionally kept for contrast. Examples:\\n\\n```python\\n# BAD: Testing mock setup instead of functionality\\nservices['transcription'].transcribe_audio.assert_not_called()\\n\\n# GOOD: Testing actual behavior  \\nassert services['state'].is_message_processed(\\\"12345\\\")\\n```\\n\\n### ✅ Excellent Patterns Observed\\n\\n1. **Real Service Usage:** Tests use actual `ServiceContainer` instances\\n2. **Appropriate Mocking Boundaries:** Only external APIs (Telegram) are mocked\\n3. **Real Data Generation:** Audio files created programmatically, not mocked\\n4. **Performance Validation:** Real benchmarks with enforced thresholds\\n5. **State Persistence Testing:** Services reloaded to verify persistence\\n\\n## Test Strategy Documentation Quality\\n\\n### 🟢 EXCELLENT: `TEST_STRATEGY.md`\\n\\nThis document demonstrates exceptional understanding of testing principles:\\n\\n- Clear philosophy: \\\"Death to Mock Abuse\\\"\\n- Detailed before/after comparisons\\n- Specific examples of improvements\\n- Professional CI/CD guidance\\n- Performance characteristics documentation\\n\\n### 🟢 EXCELLENT: `REIMPLEMENTATION_SUMMARY.md`\\n\\nComprehensive documentation of the transformation from poor to excellent testing.\\n\\n## Coverage and Organization\\n\\n### Test Categories by Markers:\\n\\n```bash\\n# Fast development feedback (excludes slow transcription)\\nuv run pytest -m \\\"not slow and not transcription\\\"\\n\\n# Integration testing with real services  \\nuv run pytest -m integration\\n\\n# Complete transcription validation\\nuv run pytest -m transcription\\n\\n# Performance benchmarks\\nuv run pytest -m performance\\n\\n# End-to-end workflows\\nuv run pytest -m e2e\\n```\\n\\n### Coverage Quality:\\n- **Functional Coverage:** ✅ Complete (all workflows covered)\\n- **Integration Coverage:** ✅ Excellent (real service interactions)\\n- **Performance Coverage:** ✅ Comprehensive (with thresh